04816nam a22007095i 9780812295559DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20182019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122955597 a10.9783/97808122955592doi  a(DE-B1597)521540  a(OCoLC)1079008480  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aCB203b.S28 2019 7aSCI0340002bisacsh04a940.12231 aSauter, Michael J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Spatial Reformation :bEuclid Between Man, Cosmos, and God /cMichael J. Sauter. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b34 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIntellectual History of the Modern Age00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. The Spatial Reformation -- tChapter 1. From Sacred Texts to Secular Space -- tChapter 2. The Renaissance and the Round Ball -- tChapter 3. Divine Melancholy -- tChapter 4. Eden’s End -- tChapter 5. Modest Ravings -- tChapter 6. Strangers to the World -- tConclusion. Prosaic Reflections -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Spatial Reformation, Michael J. Sauter offers a sweeping history of the way Europeans conceived of three-dimensional space, including the relationship between Earth and the heavens, between 1350 and 1850. He argues that this "spatial reformation" provoked a reorganization of knowledge in the West that was arguably as important as the religious Reformation. Notably, it had its own sacred text, which proved as central and was as ubiquitously embraced: Euclid's Elements. Aside from the Bible, no other work was so frequently reproduced in the early modern era. According to Sauter, its penetration and suffusion throughout European thought and experience call for a deliberate reconsideration not only of what constitutes the intellectual foundation of the early modern era but also of its temporal range.The Spatial Reformation contends that space is a human construct: that is, it is a concept that arises from the human imagination and gets expressed physically in texts and material objects. Sauter begins his examination by demonstrating how Euclidean geometry, when it was applied fully to the cosmos, estranged God from man, enabling the breakthrough to heliocentrism and, by extension, the discovery of the New World. Subsequent chapters provide detailed analyses of the construction of celestial and terrestrial globes, Albrecht Dürer's engraving Melencolia, the secularization of the natural history of the earth and man, and Hobbes's rejection of Euclid's sense of space and its effect on his political theory. Sauter's exploration culminates in the formation of a new anthropology in the eighteenth century that situated humanity in reference to spaces and places that human eyes had not actually seen. The Spatial Reformation illustrates how these disparate advancements can be viewed as resulting expressly from early modernity's embrace of Euclidean geometry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aGeometryxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aSpacexPhilosophyxHistory. 0aSpacexSocial aspectsxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Frontlist Package 2019z978311065205540uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229555940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812295559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812295559.jpg  a978-3-11-065205-5  Penn Press eBook Frontlist Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL 